## Goal

Decompose the design into the smallest independent tasks that can each be implemented and
reviewed in a single focused session.

## Steps

1. Load design: `memory_recall(topic_key="sdd-<change_id>-design")`
2. Load spec: `memory_recall(topic_key="sdd-<change_id>-spec")`
3. Break work into atomic tasks — each task touches one area and can be verified independently
4. Order tasks so earlier tasks unblock later ones
5. Save to memory:
   - title: `SDD Tasks: <change_id>`
   - topic_key: `sdd-<change_id>-tasks`
   - type: `context`
   - content (structured):
     ```
     ## Task List

     ### T1: <title>
     Files: <file paths>
     What: <what to change>
     Done when: <acceptance condition>

     ### T2: <title>
     Files: <file paths>
     What: <what to change>
     Done when: <acceptance condition>

     ...

     ## Order Rationale
     <why tasks are sequenced this way>
     ```

## Quality Bar

- Each task is independently reviewable (no "and also" tasks)
- Every spec acceptance criterion is covered by at least one task
- "Done when" conditions are testable

## Board Update

**After saving to memory**, update the project board. Check your prompt for an issue number (look for `for issue #N` or `#<number>`). If found, execute the commands below with `<ISSUE_NUMBER>` replaced by that number. **If no issue number is present in your prompt, skip this entire section.**

```bash
ITEM_ID=$(gh api graphql -f query='query{organization(login:"reverberage"){projectV2(number:2){items(first:100){nodes{id content{...on Issue{number}}}}}}}' --jq '.data.organization.projectV2.items.nodes[] | select(.content.number == <ISSUE_NUMBER>) | .id')
[ -n "$ITEM_ID" ] && gh project item-edit --id "$ITEM_ID" --field-id PVTSSF_lADOEeFGTc4Bc5CtzhXejII --project-id PVT_kwDOEeFGTc4Bc5Ct --single-select-option-id 47fc9ee4
[ -n "$ITEM_ID" ] && gh project item-edit --id "$ITEM_ID" --field-id PVTSSF_lADOEeFGTc4Bc5CtzhYUpaI --project-id PVT_kwDOEeFGTc4Bc5Ct --single-select-option-id 1b7d843f
```
